body:
Hello 🦉,

I’d like to submit a proposal for taking upon me the maintenance of this project, because AFAICT this repository is not maintained anymore.

I have worked on this project a lot, in [a fork of mine](https://github.com/xcode-actions/swift-sh), to the point of having rewritten 99% of the code.

All of this started because the way your project works has always bothered me, especially wrt. the fact it is not the actually script which is launched, but a compiled version of it, which is somewhere deep in a cache folder. That means to get the path of the script, which is something very often done in a script, one has to hack one’s way into retrieving that (e.g. by using the `_` environment variable, which works, but is oh so ugly).

So I thought to myself “there’s got to be a better way!”
And for a long time I left things at that.

Then one day, I discovered `swift run --repl`.
This command allows one to run a library package in a REPL, to test it live.

And that’s not all: when running that command, after the library is compiled, the actual arguments passed down to Swift for running the REPL are printed! (A `-I` and a `-L` option, as well as some other things I don’t remember).

So from there, it became obvious how to run the script directly: once the dependencies are computed, create a package in a cache folder, run `swift run --repl` in that package, retrieve the command line for executing Swift, and run the original script with the proper options to Swift.

Believe it or not: it works.

So I rewrote `swift-sh` fully using this new paradigm.
I now have a code that is modern and clean, and can be installed using `xcode-actions/tap/swift-sh`.

The parsing of the import directive has been fully rewritten, but the original tests all pass.

These original commands are supported:
- `swift-sh run`
- `swift-sh clean`

This is new:
- `swift-sh build`: build the script as a binary;
- `swift-sh clean`: has options to clean only parts of the cache folder;
- `swift-sh new`: create a new script (implementation in progress);
- Support for `/* */`-style comments for import sources;
- Support for setting the foreground process ID for stdin (disabled by default because for some reason Swift catches Ctrl-C, which is annoying);
- One of the most important things IMHO: `import SwiftSH_Helpers` is detected as a dependency to a product of `swift-sh` itself. This product does a bunch of `@_exported` imports, and give access to:
   - `ArgumentParser`;
   - [CLTLogger](https://github.com/xcode-actions/clt-logger) (a swift-log handler of mine, dedicated to Command Line Tools);
   - [InlineObjectConfig](https://github.com/Frizlab/InlineObjectConfig) (sugar that allows doing things like `let a = MyStruct()--{ $0.property = 42 }`, which avoids having `a` be a var);
   - `Logging`
   - [ProcessInvocation](https://github.com/xcode-actions/swift-process-invocation) (a helper on which I worked a lot, that allows launching processes easily, using the `PATH`, and with proper async support, as well as async stream support – will be sherlocked by [Subprocess](https://github.com/swiftlang/swift-subprocess) though);
   - [StreamReader](https://github.com/Frizlab/stream-reader) (a project of mine for reading streams until a certain pattern occurs, or until a number of bytes are read);
   - `SystemPackage`;
   - [UnwrapOrThrow](https://github.com/Frizlab/UnwrapOrThrow) (sugar that allows doing `let a = try myOptional ?! MyError()`);
   - [XDG](https://github.com/Frizlab/swift-xdg) (a package of mine to retrieve the XDG folders and other related utilities);
   - A convenient `MessageError` error type;
   - A `changeCurrentDirectoryPath` function, which takes a relative path, and a “path base” argument, which is either `nil` (current folder), the folder containing the script or the root of the repo containing the script. Example: `try changeCurrentDirectoryPath(.scriptRepoRoot)`.

Roadmap:
- Finish implementing `swift-sh new`;
- Implement the `edit` and `eject` commands;
- Finish implementing the different clean options.

I use that project everyday.
All my scripts are in Swift! 😊

Thanks for reading.
If you want to discuss privately you can mail me on my commit email address (requires cloning any repo of mine because it’s hidden on Github).

It would be nice if swift-sh would support scripts that contain the new `@main`. Like:

```swift
@main
struct MyTool: App {
  
  var body: some Scene {
    WindowGroup { Text("Hello World!") }
  }
}
```

Suggested implementation:
- grep the source file for `@main` or maybe `@main[\t\n ]+struct` if the script itself is not called `main.swift`
- if found, do not copy the script to `main.swift` but instead keep the original script name (like MyTool.swift)
- the hashbang line must be removed, it is only allowed in `main.swift`
- use Swift package tools version 5.5 (required for working `@main`), and add this to the `Package.swift`:
```
// swift-tools-version:5.5
...
pkg.platforms = [ .macOS(.v11) ]
```

Another option might be to use the hashbang line to configure an explicit mode? Like:
```
#!/usr/bin/swift sh #@main
```
